# AI Agent Development Rules for Yuvoi Frontend Project

## Project Overview

This is a **SvelteKit + TypeScript** project using **Vite** and **TailwindCSS** for the Yuvoi booking application.

### Key Architectural Decisions

- **Modular Architecture**: Feature-based modules organized under `src/modules/` using Functional Isolated Modules (FIM) pattern
- **Domain-Driven Design**: Each module represents a business domain (auth, etc.)
- **Error Handling**: All errors caught and handled at the store layer, not in UI components
- **Monorepo Setup**: Part of a Turborepo monorepo with shared types package
- **SvelteKit Conventions**: File-based routing with full SSR/CSR support

The app follows SvelteKit's file-based routing conventions with full support for SSR (Server-Side Rendering) and CSR (Client-Side Rendering), while organizing business logic into domain-based modules.

## Core Technologies & Versions

- **SvelteKit** (latest) - Full-stack web framework
- **Svelte 5+** - Component framework with reactive state
- **TypeScript 5.5+** - Type safety
- **Vite** - Build tool and dev server
- **TailwindCSS 4+** - Utility-first CSS framework
- **ESLint 9+** - Code linting with flat config
- **Prettier** - Code formatting

## SvelteKit File-Based Routing Architecture

### Core Routing Structure

SvelteKit uses a file-based routing system where the directory structure defines the routes:

```
src/
├── routes/
│   ├── +layout.svelte          # Root layout (wraps all pages)
│   ├── +layout.ts              # Root layout loader (shared data)
│   ├── +layout.server.ts       # Root layout server loader (SSR only)
│   ├── +page.svelte            # Homepage (/)
│   ├── +page.ts                # Page loader (client + SSR)
│   ├── +page.server.ts         # Page server loader (SSR only)
│   ├── +error.svelte           # Error boundary
│   │
│   ├── about/
│   │   ├── +page.svelte        # /about page
│   │   └── +page.ts            # /about loader
│   │
│   ├── blog/
│   │   ├── +layout.svelte      # Layout for all /blog/* routes
│   │   ├── +page.svelte        # /blog page
│   │   ├── [slug]/
│   │   │   ├── +page.svelte    # /blog/[slug] page
│   │   │   └── +page.ts        # Dynamic route loader
│   │
│   └── api/
│       └── [...path]/
│           └── +server.ts      # API endpoint handler
│
├── lib/                        # Reusable code ($lib alias)
│   ├── components/             # Svelte components
│   ├── stores/                 # Svelte stores (state management)
│   ├── utils/                  # Utility functions
│   ├── types/                  # TypeScript types
│   └── server/                 # Server-only code
│
├── app.html                    # Root HTML template
├── app.d.ts                    # TypeScript definitions
└── app.css                     # Global styles
```

### SvelteKit File Naming Conventions

| File Name | Purpose | Environment | Example |
|-----------|---------|-------------|---------|
| `+page.svelte` | Page component | Client + SSR | Route UI |
| `+page.ts` | Page load function | Client + SSR | Fetch data |
| `+page.server.ts` | Server-only load | SSR only | Secure data fetching |
| `+layout.svelte` | Layout component | Client + SSR | Shared UI wrapper |
| `+layout.ts` | Layout load function | Client + SSR | Shared data |
| `+layout.server.ts` | Server-only layout load | SSR only | Auth checks |
| `+error.svelte` | Error boundary | Client + SSR | Error handling |
| `+server.ts` | API endpoint | Server only | REST/API routes |

### Route Loading Pattern

```typescript
// +page.ts - Runs on server during SSR AND client during navigation
import type { PageLoad } from './$types';

export const load: PageLoad = async ({ fetch, params, url }) => {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/data/${params.id}`);
  const data = await response.json();

  return {
    data,
    title: 'Page Title'
  };
};
```

```typescript
// +page.server.ts - Runs ONLY on server (secure)
import type { PageServerLoad } from './$types';

export const load: PageServerLoad = async ({ locals, params }) => {
  // Access to server-only resources (DB, env variables, etc.)
  const user = locals.user;
  const privateData = await db.query('SELECT * FROM ...');

  return {
    user,
    privateData
  };
};
```

### Layout Hierarchy

Layouts nest automatically based on directory structure:

```
routes/
├── +layout.svelte              # Root (wraps everything)
│   ├── dashboard/
│   │   ├── +layout.svelte      # Dashboard layout (wraps all dashboard pages)
│   │   ├── +page.svelte        # /dashboard
│   │   └── settings/
│   │       └── +page.svelte    # /dashboard/settings
```

Result: `Root Layout > Dashboard Layout > Settings Page`

## Svelte Component Standards

### Component Structure

Always use this order in `.svelte` files:

1. `<script lang="ts">` block (or `<script context="module">` if needed)
2. `<template>` (HTML markup, no wrapper needed in Svelte)
3. `<style>` block (scoped by default)

### Script Block Pattern

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  // 1. Imports (external, then internal, then types)
  import { onMount } from 'svelte';
  import { goto } from '$app/navigation';
  import { page } from '$app/stores';
  import Button from '$lib/components/Button.svelte';
  import type { PageData } from './$types';

  // 2. Props definition
  export let data: PageData;
  export let optional: boolean = false;
  export let variant: 'primary' | 'secondary' = 'primary';

  // 3. Local state (reactive by default)
  let loading = false;
  let items = data.items;

  // 4. Reactive declarations ($: runs when dependencies change)
  $: filteredItems = items.filter(item => item.active);
  $: totalCount = items.length;

  // 5. Functions
  function handleClick() {
    loading = true;
    // logic
  }

  // 6. Lifecycle hooks
  onMount(() => {
    console.log('Component mounted');
    return () => {
      console.log('Component unmounted');
    };
  });
</script>

<div class="container">
  <h1>Total: {totalCount}</h1>
  {#each filteredItems as item (item.id)}
    <div>{item.name}</div>
  {/each}
</div>

<style>
  .container {
    /* Scoped styles */
  }
</style>
```

### Template Guidelines (Svelte Syntax)

#### Conditional Rendering

```svelte
{#if condition}
  <p>Condition is true</p>
{:else if otherCondition}
  <p>Other condition</p>
{:else}
  <p>All false</p>
{/if}
```

#### Loops

```svelte
{#each items as item, index (item.id)}
  <div>{item.name}</div>
{:else}
  <p>No items</p>
{/each}
```

#### Await Blocks

```svelte
{#await promise}
  <p>Loading...</p>
{:then result}
  <p>Result: {result}</p>
{:catch error}
  <p>Error: {error.message}</p>
{/await}
```

#### Event Handling

```svelte
<button on:click={handleClick}>Click</button>
<input on:input={(e) => value = e.currentTarget.value} />
```

#### Class Binding

```svelte
<div class="base" class:active={isActive} class:disabled>
  Content
  </div>
```

#### Two-Way Binding

```svelte
<input bind:value={name} />
<input type="checkbox" bind:checked={agreed} />
```

### Component Communication

```svelte
<!-- Parent.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import Child from './Child.svelte';

  function handleEvent(event: CustomEvent<string>) {
    console.log(event.detail);
  }
</script>

<Child value="hello" on:custom={handleEvent} />

<!-- Child.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { createEventDispatcher } from 'svelte';

  export let value: string;

  const dispatch = createEventDispatcher<{
    custom: string;
  }>();

  function triggerEvent() {
    dispatch('custom', 'data');
  }
</script>
```

## File Organization & Structure

### Architecture Philosophy

This project follows a **domain-driven, feature-based modular architecture** where each feature is a **Functional Isolated Module (FIM)**. Each module is self-contained with its own pages, components, store, types, constants, and utilities.

### Architecture Layers

```
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         UI Components                           │
│    (layout, page, component)                    │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ▲ f
                    │
┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
│         State Stores                            │
│  (business logic, API reqs, state management)   │
│                                                 │
│  Note: all Errors are caught at this layer     │
└─────────────────────────────────────────────────┘
                    ▲
        ┌───────────┼───────────┬───────────┐
        │           │           │           │
    ┌───────┐  ┌────────┐  ┌────────┐  ┌────────┐
    │ Types │  │Constants│ │ Types  │  │Constants│
    │internal│ │(internal)│ │shared/ │  │(internal)│
    │frontend│ │         │ │package │  │         │
    └───────┘  └────────┘  └────────┘  └────────┘
```

### Naming Conventions

- **Components**: PascalCase (e.g., `Button.svelte`, `UserCard.svelte`, `NavigationMenu.svelte`)
- **Routes**: kebab-case for directories (e.g., `user-settings/`)
- **Modules**: kebab-case for directories (e.g., `auth/`, `common/`)
- **Utilities**: camelCase (e.g., `formatDate.ts`, `apiClient.ts`)
- **Types**: PascalCase for types/interfaces (e.g., `User`, `ApiResponse`)
- **Stores**: camelCase files in `store/index.ts`
- **Constants**: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE (e.g., `API_BASE_URL`, `MAX_RETRIES`)

### Directory Structure

```
src/
├── lib/                          # Truly global shared stuff
│   ├── assets/                   # Global assets
│   │   ├── css/                  # Global stylesheets
│   │   ├── images/               # Global images
