## Functional Isolated Modules (FIM)

### What is a Functional Isolated Module?

A **Functional Isolated Module** is a self-contained feature domain that includes everything needed for that feature:
- UI components specific to the feature
- Page components for routes
- State management (store)
- Business logic and API calls
- Types and interfaces
- Constants and enums
- Utility functions

### When to Create a New Module

Create a new module when:
- Adding a new feature domain (e.g., `auth`, `shuttle-booking`, `payments`)
- The feature has its own business logic and state
- The feature is large enough to warrant separation (3+ components)

### Module Structure Template

When creating a new module `feature-name`:

```
src/modules/feature-name/
├── pages/              # Pages for this feature's routes
│   └── FeaturePage.svelte
├── components/         # Components used only in this feature
│   └── FeatureComponent.svelte
├── store/              # State management for this feature
│   └── index.ts        # Feature store (business logic, API calls)
├── types/              # Types specific to this feature
│   └── index.ts
├── consts/             # Constants specific to this feature
│   ├── index.ts
│   └── enums.ts
└── utils/              # Utilities specific to this feature
    └── index.ts
```

### Import Patterns

```typescript
// Importing from the same module (relative imports)
import { FeatureComponent } from '../components/FeatureComponent.svelte';
import { featureStore } from '../store';
import type { FeatureData } from '../types';
import { FEATURE_STATUS } from '../consts';

// Importing from common module (absolute imports with $modules alias)
import { Button } from '$modules/common/components/Button.svelte';
import { formatDate } from '$modules/common/utils';
import type { ApiResponse } from '$modules/common/types';

// Importing from global assets (absolute import with $lib alias)
import logo from '$lib/assets/images/logo.svg';
import '$lib/assets/css/global.css';

// Importing from shared types package (monorepo)
import type { User, Shuttle, ShuttleRequest } from '@repo/shared-types';

// Importing SvelteKit generated types
import type { PageData, PageLoad } from './$types';

// Importing SvelteKit utilities
import { goto } from '$app/navigation';
import { page } from '$app/stores';
import { browser } from '$app/environment';
```

### Path Aliases Configuration

Ensure your `svelte.config.js` and `tsconfig.json` have these aliases configured:

```javascript
// svelte.config.js
export default {
  kit: {
    alias: {
      $lib: 'src/lib',
      $modules: 'src/modules',
      $routes: 'src/routes'
    }
  }
};
```

```json
// tsconfig.json
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "paths": {
      "$lib": ["./src/lib"],
      "$lib/*": ["./src/lib/*"],
      "$modules": ["./src/modules"],
      "$modules/*": ["./src/modules/*"],
      "@repo/shared-types": ["../../packages/shared-types/src"]
    }
  }
}
```

### The `common` Module

The `common` module is special—it contains code shared across multiple features:
- **Reusable UI components** (Button, Modal, Input, Card, etc.)
- **Common utilities** (date formatting, validation, API client)
- **Shared types** (ApiResponse, PaginatedData, etc.)
- **UI state** (theme, sidebar open/closed, notifications)

**Rule**: Only put code in `common` if it's used by 2+ other modules. Otherwise, keep it in the feature module.

## State Management with Svelte Stores

### Store Architecture (Error Handling Layer)

**Critical**: All errors must be caught and handled at the **store layer**. This is the error boundary for your application. UI components should never need to handle API errors directly.

### Module Store Pattern

```typescript
// src/modules/auth/store/index.ts
import { writable, derived } from 'svelte/store';
import type { User } from '../types';

interface AuthState {
  user: User | null;
  loading: boolean;
  error: string | null;
}

function createAuthStore() {
  const { subscribe, set, update } = writable<AuthState>({
    user: null,
    loading: false,
    error: null
  });

  return {
    subscribe,

    // Actions with error handling at this layer
    async login(email: string, password: string) {
      update(state => ({ ...state, loading: true, error: null }));

      try {
        const response = await fetch('/api/auth/login', {
          method: 'POST',
          headers: { 'Content-Type': 'application/json' },
          body: JSON.stringify({ email, password })
        });

        if (!response.ok) {
          throw new Error('Invalid credentials');
        }

        const user = await response.json();
        update(state => ({ ...state, user, loading: false }));

        return { success: true };
      } catch (error) {
        const errorMessage = error instanceof Error ? error.message : 'Login failed';
        update(state => ({ ...state, error: errorMessage, loading: false }));

        // Optionally: show toast notification here
        console.error('Login error:', errorMessage);

        return { success: false, error: errorMessage };
      }
    },

    async logout() {
      update(state => ({ ...state, loading: true }));

      try {
        await fetch('/api/auth/logout', { method: 'POST' });
        set({ user: null, loading: false, error: null });
      } catch (error) {
        // Even if logout fails, clear local state
        set({ user: null, loading: false, error: null });
      }
    },

    clearError() {
      update(state => ({ ...state, error: null }));
    }
  };
}

export const authStore = createAuthStore();

// Derived stores for computed state
export const isAuthenticated = derived(
  authStore,
  $auth => !!$auth.user
);

export const isLoading = derived(
  authStore,
  $auth => $auth.loading
);
```

### Using Module Stores in Components

```svelte
<!-- src/modules/auth/pages/LoginPage.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import { authStore, isAuthenticated } from '../store';
  import { Button } from '$modules/common/components/Button.svelte';

  let email = '';
  let password = '';

  // Auto-subscribe with $ prefix (unsubscribes automatically)
  $: loading = $authStore.loading;
  $: error = $authStore.error;

  async function handleLogin() {
    const result = await authStore.login(email, password);

    if (result.success) {
      // Navigate to dashboard or home
      console.log('Login successful');
    }
    // Error is already handled in the store layer
  }
</script>

<div class="login-page">
  <h1>Login</h1>

  {#if error}
    <div class="error-message">{error}</div>
  {/if}

  <form on:submit|preventDefault={handleLogin}>
    <input
      type="email"
      bind:value={email}
      placeholder="Email"
      disabled={loading}
    />
    <input
      type="password"
      bind:value={password}
      placeholder="Password"
      disabled={loading}
    />

    <Button type="submit" disabled={loading}>
      {loading ? 'Logging in...' : 'Login'}
    </Button>
  </form>
</div>
```

### Using Module Pages in Routes

```svelte
<!-- src/routes/login/+page.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import LoginPage from '$modules/auth/pages/LoginPage.svelte';
</script>

<LoginPage />
```

This pattern separates:
- **Routes** (`src/routes/`) - SvelteKit routing structure
- **Module pages** (`src/modules/*/pages/`) - Actual page implementation with logic

### Derived Stores

```typescript
import { derived, writable } from 'svelte/store';

export const todos = writable([
  { id: 1, text: 'Task 1', done: false },
  { id: 2, text: 'Task 2', done: true }
]);

export const completedTodos = derived(
  todos,
  $todos => $todos.filter(todo => todo.done)
);

export const todoCount = derived(
  todos,
  $todos => $todos.length
);
```

### Readable Stores

```typescript
import { readable } from 'svelte/store';

export const time = readable(new Date(), (set) => {
  const interval = setInterval(() => {
    set(new Date());
  }, 1000);

  return () => clearInterval(interval);
});
```

## Data Loading Patterns

### Client + Server Loading (+page.ts)

```typescript
// src/routes/blog/[slug]/+page.ts
import type { PageLoad } from './$types';

export const load: PageLoad = async ({ fetch, params }) => {
  const response = await fetch(`/api/blog/${params.slug}`);

  if (!response.ok) {
    throw new Error('Failed to load blog post');
  }

  const post = await response.json();

  return {
    post
  };
};
```

### Server-Only Loading (+page.server.ts)

```typescript
// src/routes/admin/+page.server.ts
import type { PageServerLoad } from './$types';
import { redirect } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export const load: PageServerLoad = async ({ locals }) => {
  if (!locals.user || !locals.user.isAdmin) {
    throw redirect(302, '/login');
  }

  // Access server-only resources
  const users = await db.users.findMany();

  return {
    users
  };
};
```

### Form Actions

```typescript
// src/routes/login/+page.server.ts
import type { Actions } from './$types';
import { fail, redirect } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export const actions = {
  login: async ({ request, cookies }) => {
    const data = await request.formData();
    const email = data.get('email');
    const password = data.get('password');

    if (!email || !password) {
      return fail(400, { email, missing: true });
    }

    const user = await authenticateUser(email, password);

    if (!user) {
      return fail(400, { email, incorrect: true });
    }

    cookies.set('session', user.sessionId, { path: '/' });

    throw redirect(303, '/dashboard');
  }
} satisfies Actions;
```

```svelte
<!-- src/routes/login/+page.svelte -->
<script lang="ts">
  import type { ActionData } from './$types';

  export let form: ActionData;
</script>

<form method="POST" action="?/login">
  <input name="email" value={form?.email ?? ''} />
  {#if form?.missing}
    <p>Email and password are required</p>
  {/if}
  {#if form?.incorrect}
    <p>Invalid credentials</p>
  {/if}
  <input name="password" type="password" />
  <button type="submit">Login</button>
</form>
```

## API Endpoints (+server.ts)

### Creating API Routes

```typescript
// src/routes/api/users/+server.ts
import type { RequestHandler } from './$types';
import { json } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export const GET: RequestHandler = async ({ url }) => {
  const limit = Number(url.searchParams.get('limit')) || 10;

  const users = await db.users.findMany({ limit });

  return json(users);
};

export const POST: RequestHandler = async ({ request }) => {
  const data = await request.json();

  const user = await db.users.create(data);

  return json(user, { status: 201 });
};
```

### Dynamic API Routes

```typescript
// src/routes/api/users/[id]/+server.ts
import type { RequestHandler } from './$types';
import { json, error } from '@sveltejs/kit';

export const GET: RequestHandler = async ({ params }) => {
  const user = await db.users.findById(params.id);

  if (!user) {
    throw error(404, 'User not found');
  }

  return json(user);
};

export const PATCH: RequestHandler = async ({ params, request }) => {
  const updates = await request.json();
  const user = await db.users.update(params.id, updates);

  return json(user);
};

export const DELETE: RequestHandler = async ({ params }) => {
  await db.users.delete(params.id);

  return new Response(null, { status: 204 });
};
```

## TypeScript Standards

### Type Definitions

```typescript
// $lib/types/models.ts

export type UserRole = 'admin' | 'user' | 'guest';

export interface User {
  id: string;
  email: string;
  name: string;
  role: UserRole;
  createdAt: Date;
}

export interface ApiResponse<T> {
  data: T;
  error?: string;
  meta?: {
    page: number;
    total: number;
  };
}

export type LoadingState = 'idle' | 'loading' | 'success' | 'error';
```

### SvelteKit Generated Types

Always use generated types from `./$types`:

```typescript
import type { PageData, PageLoad } from './$types';

export const load: PageLoad = async ({ fetch }) => {
  // TypeScript knows the return type
  return {
    title: 'Page Title',
    count: 42
  };
};
```

```svelte
<script lang="ts">
  import type { PageData } from './$types';

  export let data: PageData;
  // TypeScript knows data.title and data.count exist
</script>
```

### Type Safety Best Practices

- **Avoid `any`** - use `unknown` when type is truly unknown
- **Use strict mode** - enable in `tsconfig.json`
- **Type all function parameters and returns**
- **Use type guards** for narrowing
- **Leverage discriminated unions** for complex state

```typescript
type Result<T> =
  | { success: true; data: T }
  | { success: false; error: string };

function handleResult<T>(result: Result<T>) {
  if (result.success) {
    console.log(result.data); // TypeScript knows data exists
  } else {
    console.error(result.error); // TypeScript knows error exists
  }
}
```

